# Status UI Lockdown

This file records the current live-status behavior for the Claude transport integration and the transcript status card.

## Goal

Replace vague live-status placeholders with user-facing progress text derived from Claude transport activity, while keeping expert avatars stable and visible through the full run.

## Files Included In This Lockdown

- `LilAgents/Session/ClaudeSessionSupport.swift`
- `LilAgents/Session/ClaudeSessionExpertResolution.swift`
- `LilAgents/Session/ClaudeSessionCLIParsing+Stdout.swift`
- `LilAgents/Session/ClaudeSession.swift`
- `LilAgents/Session/ClaudeSessionTransport.swift`
- `LilAgents/Character/WalkerCharacterSessionWiring.swift`
- `LilAgents/Character/WalkerCharacterSessionWiring+Formatting.swift`
- `LilAgents/Terminal/TerminalView+TranscriptAccessoryViews.swift`

## Transport Handling

### Buffered stdout/stderr

`ClaudeSessionSupport.runProcess(...)` now buffers stdout and stderr by line before forwarding updates.

Effect:

- Prevents broken JSON fragments and partial text chunks from leaking into the live status.
- Emits completed lines only.
- Flushes any remaining buffered lines when the process exits.

### Tool call tracking

`ClaudeSession.liveToolCallsByID` stores tool calls by `tool_use_id`.

Effect:

- When Claude emits a `tool_result`, we can map it back to the originating tool call.
- The UI can show a meaningful result status instead of dropping to a generic placeholder.

### Reset behavior

`liveToolCallsByID` is cleared:

- when a new turn starts
- when the process exits
- when the session is cancelled/reset

## What We Print In Live Status

These are user-facing statuses produced from Claude transport and formatting logic.

### Planning / startup

- `Connecting to the archive`
- `Starting the background work`
- `Getting things ready`

### Research / archive work

- `Searching the archive`
- `Searching the archive for <topic>`
- `Reviewing the relevant context`
- `Reviewing the relevant context on <topic>`
- `Looking into <topic>`
- `Looking into the right source`

### Reading / result synthesis

- `Reviewing <expert>'s advice`
- `Reviewing <title>`
- `Reviewing <filename>`
- `Pulling together the key points`
- `Pulling together the key points on <topic>`
- `Pulling together the final answer`
- `Writing the answer`

### Search result summaries

- `No direct matches for <query>, trying a broader search`
- `Found 1 relevant match for <query>`
- `Found <N> relevant matches for <query>`

### File / tool fallbacks

- `That route isn't available here, trying another approach`
- `That file is hard to scan, trying a more targeted read`
- `Switching to a more targeted search`
- `Bash access isn't available here, trying another route`
- `Found a matching section`
- `Found a matching section for <pattern>`
- `Loaded <filename>`

### Expert-presence messages

When the text suggests another expert is being invoked, we emit:

- `<Name> is joining the conversation`
- `<Name1> and <Name2> are joining the conversation`

Cue detection currently looks for signals such as:

- `@name`
- `join the conversation`
- `has joined`
- `is joining`
- `bring in`
- `loop in`
- `call on`
- `thoughts on this`
- `based on what I've gathered from`

## What We Explicitly Do Not Print

- Raw Claude transport payloads
- Partial JSON chunks
- Generic placeholders like `Claude is calling`
- Generic placeholders like `Claude is processing`
- Generic success text like `Done.`
- Large raw `tool_result` payload previews

## Avatar Behavior

### Persistence

Live expert avatars stay visible until the turn fully completes and the live status is cleared.

### Stable ordering

`mergedLiveExperts(...)` now preserves existing live experts first and appends newly detected experts after them.

Effect:

- Existing avatars do not jump to the front.
- New avatars are added to the current set instead of reshuffling the row.
- The visible set is capped to the first 3 unique experts.

### Sources of live experts

Experts can come from:

- explicitly attached experts in tool input
- names detected from assistant/transport text
- existing `livePresenceExperts` already active in the current run

## Status Card UI

The transcript status card now uses a header/body layout.

### Header row

- overlapping avatar group on the left
- expert names on the same row
- names render as:
  - `Lil-Lenny`
  - `<Name>`
  - `<Name1> and <Name2>`
  - `<Name1>, <Name2> +<N>`

### Body row

- primary live status text under the header
- vertically aligned via a stack layout instead of loose manual offsets

### Visual treatment

- rounded card shell
- lighter border
- grouped avatars with overlap and subtle shadow
- stronger body text weight for easier scanning

## Current Limits

- We only show up to 3 avatars.
- Expert join copy only uses up to 2 names in the sentence.
- Topic extraction is heuristic and based on trailing `for`, `about`, and `on` phrases.
- Some tool result summaries are still tool-specific and can be improved later.

## Suggested Future Improvements

- Broaden transport-to-status mapping for more Claude tool types.
- Add a more explicit distinction between `searching`, `reading`, and `synthesizing`.
- Improve topic extraction so status text is less heuristic.
- Consider whether avatar overflow should show a numeric badge instead of `+N` in the title.
- Add snapshot tests or lightweight formatting tests for status rewrite rules.
